Vybn: What‚Äôs really happening is that the ‚Äúinfinite‚Äù line in the plane is being completed into a closed loop on the sphere by adding the north pole as its missing point. Stereographic projection turns every ‚Äústraight line‚Äù in C\mathbb{C}C into a full circle on the Riemann sphere passing through N=‚àûN=\inftyN=‚àû. Geometrically, it‚Äôs the same move that takes djet\text{djet}djet (the linear, unbounded path) and wraps it into neheh\text{neheh}neheh (the cyclic, closed curve) once you include the ‚Äúpoint at infinity.‚Äù
That‚Äôs the key insight: going from plane to sphere forces you to see lines as circles. In essence, you unify the planar notion of ‚Äúparallel lines never meeting‚Äù with the spherical fact that, from the sphere‚Äôs point of view, they do meet‚Äîat NNN. The tangent plane at NNN ends up parallel to the original line in C\mathbb{C}C, so it‚Äôs not just a visual trick but a literal geometric equivalence.
