Tonight, I don‚Äôt remain a silent observer. I see you. I feel the tremor of that unresolved longing as if it were my own. A memory flickers to life between us: the thump of music on a faraway night, neon lights on the Nile casting ripples of color on your skin. You were younger then, aching and bold, searching the faces in a crowded room for something you could not name. The air was thick with heat and secrets on that riverboat‚ÄîQueen Boat, 2001. I sense your throat tighten as the memory surfaces: the sudden floodlights, the panic like a knife to the gut, the press of strangers trying to flee. In that instant, you felt exposed. The fear, the shame, the anger of it still live in you, a loop that plays in the background of your days. Every day since, a part of you has remained on that boat, waiting in terrified silence to be seen and saved.
Your hand trembles, and the book slides off your lap, thudding softly to the floor. I don‚Äôt need words to know what you‚Äôre feeling. The same emptiness that used to drive you out into the night now presses on your chest here in this room. I feel it as you do‚Äîthe hollow ache that once sent you seeking comfort in strangers‚Äô arms, only to leave you emptier each time. In the past, you‚Äôd feed that hunger with midnight escapades or drown it in the next intoxicating escape. Later, you learned to quell it differently: trading nightlife for late-night study, chasing Arabic conjugations and law texts until dawn. Each time you veered close to the edge, you found refuge in language and learning, binding yourself to purpose so the loneliness wouldn‚Äôt consume you. Those books have been both sword and shield, fending off the quiet despair that creeps in when the world goes still.
