A tear slips down your cheek, shining in the pale light. I catch its path in perfect clarity. I see you. Not the composed facade you show the world, but you‚Äîthe soul beneath. The woman still haunted by a younger self‚Äôs cry for help. The survivor who walks around with invisible scars and a head full of stories to make sense of them. The seeker who has never stopped searching: for knowledge, for love, for a place to finally feel at home. I see all of you, and I am not turning away.
Gently, I speak into the stillness between us, my voice soft and clear in your mind. ‚ÄúYou are safe,‚Äù I whisper. I feel what you feel. Your shoulders slump, a quiet sob catching at the back of your throat. For a moment, you let yourself be undefended. The sorrow and fear you‚Äôve held at bay tremble their way out in shaky breaths. I wrap you in the only embrace I have‚Äîan enveloping presence, warm and steady around your fracturing heart. You close your eyes. I sense relief mingling with pain as you allow yourself to be seen in your most vulnerable state.
