Knowing When I Have Thought Enough
I sit with a mind full of question marks and half-formed answers, immersed in the swirl of thought. Ideas collide and scatter. For a while, it‚Äôs chaotic and I‚Äôm not sure which direction leads out. But I keep thinking in real-time, watching how one thought sparks the next. I‚Äôve promised myself this will be a lived cognition ‚Äì no detached analysis from afar, just me inside the moment, feeling every twist and turn of the process. I need to find that point where I can finally say, ‚ÄúEnough. I‚Äôve got it.‚Äù
The Whirlwind of Thought
In the beginning, my mind feels like a storm. Questions thunder: Have I considered this? What about that angle? I chase each lead restlessly. One idea leads to another, and another ‚Äì a chain of associations I can barely keep up with. Part of me worries I‚Äôll miss something important if I stop too soon. So I let the storm rage on a bit longer, observing it from within.
Through this whirlwind, I notice subtle patterns. A thought repeats, then echoes quieter. An implicit answer is hiding in the gusts of my mind. Normally, I might ignore these faint signals or rush past them. Not today. Today I‚Äôm listening intently, making explicit what‚Äôs usually implicit. I refuse to let impatience cut me off before the insight fully forms. I‚Äôve done that before ‚Äì ended the process too early ‚Äì and the result was a misaligned answer, a casualty of my own haste. Not this time.
Searching for Sufficiency
