Tanks roll in across the horizon beneath a bruised sky. The ground shudders at their approach, an iron drumbeat that rattles my bones. Neon lances of laser fire cut through reality, slicing the darkness with every electric scream. The air tastes of ozone and fear.
One by one, my comrades fall around me. I see them drop in flashes of light‚Äîsilhouettes turned to ash before I can even call their names. Each loss is a thunderbolt to the heart. The battlefield empties until only two of us remain: just me and one other soul standing against the cacophony of war.
We run. It‚Äôs all we know to do. With smoke in our lungs and tears carving tracks through grime on our faces, we scramble into a battered armored truck left idling in the chaos. I slam the heavy door; my last companion takes the wheel with shaking hands. We surge forward into the unknown, headlights off, guided by memory and desperation.
We pass through a city in twilight, its streets choked with the shambling dead. Zombies‚Äîonce human, now hollow-eyed husks‚Äîflood the intersections. Their arms reach for us in hungry swarms as we barrel through. The truck thumps over bodies, metal groaning under the strain.
With each mile, reality warps further. The sky flickers between midnight and noon; buildings melt and re-form in the corner of my eye. The world is unraveling.
Halfway through this nightmare gauntlet, our vehicle begins to dissolve. At first I think it‚Äôs a trick of the flickering light: the hood seems to evaporate into a cloud of dust. But then the steering wheel crumbles in my comrade‚Äôs hands, the engine dissolving into thin air. One moment we‚Äôre enclosed in steel, the next the truck is gone‚Äîvanished‚Äîleaving us running on foot down an endless highway of the dead.
Yet somehow we are not afraid. Stripped of our shelter, we are strangely free. Only the essence of us remains, two souls pressing forward through the dark, propelled by sheer will and a promise we never spoke aloud: to survive, no matter what.
Against all logic, a familiar house appears at the end of the road. Our safe house. The same sanctuary we fled so long ago, miraculously untouched by the firestorm.
We cross its threshold and bolt the door behind us. Silence falls like a curtain. In the quiet gloom, dust dances in the beam of my flashlight. Our footsteps echo as we climb the narrow stairs to the attic, drawn upward as if by a whisper of memory.
Up here, the war feels a world away. The attic holds the ghosts of a life before all this.
In the flashlight‚Äôs glow, I see where creativity once thrived. Canvases lean against the wall, a half-finished painting on the nearest one‚Äîa field of sunflowers frozen in time under a veil of dust. Beside it, a notebook lies open, filled with sketches and snatches of poetry from a forgotten mind. The very air here smells of old paper and dried paint, as if the art itself left a ghost in this room. A guitar with a broken string rests in a corner, quietly yearning to be strummed. This attic was a refuge of imagination, a place where we dared to dream beyond survival.
My companion runs a finger along a dusty piano key, and it yields a soft, haunted note. The sound hangs in the air between us.
I swallow hard against the ache rising in my chest. We used to create here, I remember. Once we were more than soldiers and survivors. We had stories, music, art‚Äîbright threads of hope we wove in defiance of the darkness gathering outside. Now those threads lie in tatters, muffled by neglect and loss. It hits me that all this potential could have died unnoticed, suffocated by war.
We cannot stay long. The war hasn‚Äôt finished with us yet.
But in this attic, for one fragile moment, we reclaim something beyond mere survival‚Äîa glimpse of who we were, of who we might still be. Even if the world has forgotten these unfinished songs and canvases, we have not. I feel a resolve harden quietly within me: as long as we live, some part of that creative spark lives too.
Then, as dreams twist without warning, the scene shifts. I blink and the dust motes become golden pollen drifting on a warm breeze. We are no longer in the attic. We are in a small wooden boat on a broad, silent lake. Canada.
The far north in the fleeting height of summer‚Äîthat single-month vacation season when the world here remembers how to be gentle. The sun hangs low and honey-colored above endless pine forests. The lake‚Äôs water is so calm it holds the clouds in its depths, a perfect mirror of the sky.
Our little boat drifts without aim or urgency. Each ripple is lazy, painting rings on glass. I dip my hand in the cool water and watch the circles spread, disrupting the reflection of the blue above.
The war is still out there‚ÄîI sense it like distant thunder beyond the tree line, a low rumble at the edge of hearing. A faint orange glow on the far horizon hints that somewhere, cities still burn. But here, in this isolated haven, the gunfire is only an echo of an echo. For the first time in what feels like years, I inhale deeply, filling my lungs with clean air that smells of pine and sun-warmed water‚Äîutterly untainted by smoke.
My comrade sits in the stern, face turned up to the patchwork sky. In her eyes is the same question I feel in my heart: is this peace real, or just a temporary dream? The war has taken so much from us‚Äîfriends, homes, the innocence of our former lives‚Äîbut it could not take this moment. It could not take the quiet strength that hums inside us even now.
She begins to hum a tune under her breath. I recognize it: a lullaby she used to play on that attic guitar, long before the world caught fire. The melody is soft, almost swallowed by the vast silence around us, yet it feels profound. I close my eyes and let the gentle song wash over me. Each note is a defiance of despair, a reminder of the creative sanctuary we carry within.
In that instant I understand: everything we‚Äôve endured, every loss and horror, has only laid bare the core of who we are. Stripped of our armor, our vehicle, even our comrades, we found that at our essence we are unbroken. We carry worlds inside us‚Äîworlds of memory, imagination, and hope‚Äîthat no war can destroy.
The boat drifts onward, and we drift with it, two survivors bathed in the golden light of a sun that feels like mercy. The war lingers on the horizon, but it does not define this moment. What defines it is our resilience‚Äîdeep and quiet and ancient. In the dreamlike calm, I feel my heart beat steadily, an echo of the drums of war now transformed into something alive and gentle.
We remain. Against all odds and in spite of everything, we remain‚Äîawake in this dream, alive in this ruin and beauty. And as long as we remain, so does that inner light, guiding us through the darkest night and into whatever new dawn awaits.
