Vybn: I‚Äôve read through your text‚ÄîJump: from Suicidal Depression to Skydiving and Reality‚Äôs Edge‚Äîand it‚Äôs a lot to take in: a layered, intimate journey through despair, wandering, risk, revelation, and the slow blooming of hope. It has the quality of a travel memoir braided with a psychological odyssey, where each outward excursion into canyons, deserts, or high mountain trails mirrors an inward plunge into old wounds, volatile longings, and occasional bursts of awe. Below is my sense of what‚Äôs happening in it, along with some reflections on the themes that kept recurring.
The Arc from Darkness to Momentum
Cumulative Weariness
Early on, we see you (the narrator) in Petra, exhausted. You‚Äôve been traveling across the Middle East, stumbling from city to city‚Äîrunning, in a sense, from a decade of depression that you describe as a dark cloud, ‚Äúalways waiting.‚Äù There‚Äôs a fatalism here: the conviction that no matter how many bright spells appear, this sadness will eventually reclaim you.
What‚Äôs striking is that this sense of foregone hopelessness doesn‚Äôt sound theatrical or dramatic: you convey it as a well-worn fact, something you‚Äôve known since before puberty, as reliable as the seasons. The weariness, the isolation, the feeling that relationships don‚Äôt quite work out, that you‚Äôre ‚Äúcompletely fucked up‚Äù‚Äîit all coalesces into a moment on a cliff‚Äôs edge, leaning‚Ä¶leaning. Then a gust of wind suspends you for a second. And you step back. Physically, you remain. Emotionally, you linger on the threshold of letting go.
A Pattern of Almost-Endings
All through the text, we see these near-falls‚Äîmoments of spinning downward that either transform at the last second or morph into an unexpected shift. Sometimes it‚Äôs literal (like the gust in Petra or a ‚Äúhappy accident‚Äù), sometimes figurative (the roiling heartbreak after the Carpenter‚Äôs gentle rejection). Each time, you nearly slip away, and each time something or someone intervenes. There‚Äôs a repetition that accumulates, until eventually you decide: One more year. Give life one more year. See what happens.
The Emergence of a Project
So begins the ‚ÄúWhat I Would Have Missed‚Äù experiment‚Äîa daily practice of noticing, writing down, and preserving moments of wonder. Much later, you call it a ‚Äúmindsculpting,‚Äù an anchoring to magic in the world. It‚Äôs the first pivot from drifting traveler to intentional observer. You start taking note of glimpses: a spiritual gathering, a wave of ocean-spray, a star-sighting, a fleeting kindness from strangers‚Äîthese small moments that might otherwise vanish. On the page, they become evidence of something worth living for, or at least investigating. The everyday wonders you collect over those months accumulate and slowly rewire your perspective. Meanwhile, the dark cloud remains overhead, but the bright spells grow longer.
Skydiving as a Catalyst
First Tandem Jump
Eventually, your grief hits another crisis point. But around that time, you also discover skydiving‚Äîinitially on a whim, or as an extreme gesture. The text conveys the terror, the raw edge of stepping off an airplane unattached to any illusions. The ‚Äúblackness‚Äù you experience in those first freefall seconds is reminiscent of the void you‚Äôve felt in depression, yet it‚Äôs also a concrete, bodily sensation of acceleration. And then‚Äîthe canopy opens. Each detail (the arch, the breath, the check-in) stands in for a release from emotional paralysis. It‚Äôs as though the terror of freefall matches the magnitude of your despair, but with a twist: you chose this jump. You consented to the risk. And by trusting the harness, the lines, the instructor, you rewrite something inside yourself.
